gomodel:SYNGO_5184  a     owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Rationale: Figure 1i-j: immunofluorescence staining for endogenous PSD95 (DLG4) and overexpressed GFP-DCLK1 in cultured hippocampal neurons showed DCLK1 localization to dendrites and dendritic spines.\n\nFigure 4: excitatory postsynaptic development is negatively regulated by (long form) DCLK1. Overexpression of GFP-DCLK1 reduced spine density and mushroom-spine numbers. shRNA knockdown of DCLK1 increased spine density, volume and mushroom-spine numbers.. Experimental description: Mice were used throughout the study; knockouts, shRNA and GFP contructs.\n\n\"Golgi staining of the hippocampal CA1 area prepared from wild-type or DCLK1-/- mice\"\n\n\"The cDNA of mouse wild-type DCLK1 sequence was amplified by PCR and inserted into pEGFP-N1 (Clontech) to generate DCLK1-GFP\"\n\nRNAi:\n\"The RNAi-targeting sequence for DCLK1 (5'-GGTTCGATTCTACAGA AAT-3') was as previously reported17. The targeting sequence for DCLK2 (5'-GCAGGTTACTTGTCTGCAAGA-3') was designed ab initio and its effect was confirmed by co-transfection with DCLK2-GFP. These oligonucleotides were ligated into the shRNA expression vector (pSilencer 2.0-U6; Invitrogen) and transfected into cells using the Effectene transfection reagent (Qiagen). Stealth RNAi Negative Control Duplexes (Invitrogen) were used as control shRNAs. The sequence for a resistant form of DCLK1 was designed by introducing three-point mutations into the original sequences (5'-GGTCCGATTTTACAGG AAT-3').\"" ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2514-0216" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-4973-5732" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2286-1587" ;
        dc:date           "2023-02-27" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_BP_5184" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_10090" .

